rCollins]]\n|<ref name=leung>[https://www.ctvnews.ca/entertainment/carrianne-leung-wins-10-000-short-fiction-prize-for-that-time-i-loved-you-1.4447878 \"Carrianne Leung wins $10,000 short fiction prize for 'That Time I Loved You'\"]. [[CTV News]], June 1, 2019.</ref>\n|- style=\"background:lightgreen;\"\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center; font-weight:normal; background-color:lightgreen\" |{{sort|20192|[[2019 in literature|2019]]}}\n|{{sortname|Paige|Cooper}}\n|''Zolitude''\n|[[Biblioasis]]\n|<ref name=leung/>\n|- style=\"background:lightgreen;\"\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center; font-weight:normal; background-color:lightgreen\" |{{sort|20193|[[2019 in literature|2019]]}}\n|{{sortname|Erin Frances|Fisher}}\n|''That Tiny Life''\n|[[House of Anansi]]\n|<ref name=leung/>\n|- style=\"background:transparent;\"\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center; font-weight:normal; background-color:transparent\" |{{sort|20194|[[2019 in literature|2019]]}}\n|{{sortname|Djamila|Ibrahim}}\n|''Things Are Good Now''\n|[[House of Anansi]]\n|<ref name=2019shortlist>[https://quillandquire.com/omni/debut-short-fiction-celebrated-on-danuta-gleed-shortlist/ \"Debut short-fiction celebrated on Danuta Gleed shortlist\"]. ''[[Quill & Quire]]'', May 9, 2019.</ref>\n|- style=\"background:transparent;\"\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center; font-weight:normal; background-color:transparent\" |{{sort|20195|[[2019 in literature|2019]]}}\n|{{sortname|Marianne|Micros}}\n|''Eye''\n|[[Guernica Editions]]\n|<ref name=2019shortlist/>\n|}\n\n:1.{{note|a}} Comeau's ''Overqualified'' was withdrawn as it was not his debut short fiction collection. He already self-published ''It\u2019s Too Late to Say I\u2019m Sorry'' in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thecoast.ca/ArtAttack/archives/2010/05/18/joey-comeau-shortlisted-for-10000-literary-award |title=Update: Joey Comeau withdrawn from $10,000 literary award |newspaper=The Coast |date=18 May 2010 |author=Sue Carter Flinn |accessdate=20 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140705205733/http://www.thecoast.ca/ArtAttack/archives/2010/05/18/joey-comeau-shortlisted-for-10000-literary-award |archivedate=5 July 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n;General\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120930073607/http://www.writersunion.ca/danuta-gleed Official site of the Danuta Gleed Literary Awards with a list of awardees]\n*[http://www.canadianauthors.net/awards/danuta_gleed_literary_award/ List of winners, runners-up and other shortlisted people]\n;Specific\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Canadian fiction awards]]\n[[Category:Short story awards]]\n[[Category:First book awards]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1998]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name           = Danuta Gleed Literary Award\n| image          = \n| imagesize      = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| description    = Canadian short fiction collections\n| presenter      = [[Writers' Union of Canada]]\n| country        = Canada\n| reward         = \n| year           = 1998\n| year2          = \n| holder         = \n}}\nThe '''Danuta Gleed Literary Award''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] national literary prize, awarded since 1998. It recognizes the best debut short fiction collection by a Canadian author in English language.<ref name=\"Official\">{{cite web |url=http://www.writersunion.ca/danuta-gleed#.UALX1JEbi4o |title=Danuta Gleed |publisher=The Writers' Union of Canada |accessdate=15 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930073607/http://www.writersunion.ca/danuta-gleed#.UALX1JEbi4o |archivedate=30 September 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> The annual prize was founded by John Gleed in honour of his late wife, the Canadian writer [[Danuta Gleed]], whose favourite literary genre was short fiction, and is presented by The [[Writers' Union of Canada]]. The incomes of her ''One for the Chosen'', a collection of short stories published posthumously in 1997 by BuschekBooks and released by [[Frances Itani]] and Susan Zettell, assist in funding the award.<ref name=\"Official\"/>\n\nInitially [[C$]]5,000, the prize money increased to C$10,000 in 2004.<ref name=\"First\">{{cite web|url=http://www.writersunion.ca/news/danuta-gleed-award-2003|title=Danuta Gleed Award 2003|publisher=The Writers' Union of Canada|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> The runners-up each receive C$500.<ref name=\"Official\"/>  The nominations must be submitted before the end of January.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.writersunion.ca/sites/all/files/attachments/2011_danutagleed_submission_guidelines_and_form.pdf|title=The Danuta Gleed Literary Award|format=PDF|publisher=The Writers' Union of Canada|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> The year's [[shortlist]] is chosen by a jury.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://arts.nationalpost.com/2012/05/09/danuta-gleed-literary-award/ |author=Mark Medley |title=Danuta Gleed Literary Award reveals shortlist |newspaper=[[National Post]] |date=9 May 2012 |accessdate=13 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130129120807/http://arts.nationalpost.com/2012/05/09/danuta-gleed-literary-award/ |archivedate=29 January 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> The varying jury is composed of Canadian writers, literary critics and publishers, such as [[Gail Anderson-Dargatz]], Robin McGrath and [[Hal Niedzviecki]] in 2012 or [[Douglas Glover (writer)|Douglas Glover]], [[J. Jill Robinson]] and [[Claire Holden Rothman]] in 2011.<ref name=\"2012 Jury\">{{cite web|url=http://www.writersunion.ca/sites/all/files/attachments/2010_danuta_gleed_literary_award_winner.pdf|title=Winner Announced for Danuta Gleed Literary Award|format=PDF|publisher=The Writers' Union of Canada|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe first winning work was Curtis Gillespie's ''The Progress of an Object in Motion''.\n\nIn 2010, [[Joey Comeau]]'s ''[[Overqualified (short story collection)|Overqualified]]'' was withdrawn, as the writer already published a debut work.  Only two books were shortlisted in 2010 (the fewest in the history of the award).  However, the 2010 judges called the winning work 'Wax Boats' by Sarah Roberts \"truly remarkable,\" speaking of her versatility and her convincing writing in every conceivable voice, and likening her to Stephen Leacock's Sunshine Sketches of a Little Town for the modern age.\n\n== Winners and nominees==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Key\n! Meaning\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:#B0C4DE\"|\n| Winners\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:lightgreen\"|\n| Runners-up\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:transparent\"| \n| Other short-listed people\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" width=\"100%\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|-\n! width=\"7%\" scope=\"col\"|Year Awarded\n! width=\"28%\" scope=\"col\"|Author(s)\n! width=\"35%\" scope=\"col\"|Book\n! width=\"26%\"|Publisher\n! width=\"4%\" class=\"unsortable\"|Ref.\n|- style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center; font-weight:normal; background:#B0C4DE;\"|{{sort|1998|[[1997 in literature|1998]]}}\n|{{sortname|Curtis|Gillespie|nolink=1}}\n|''The Progress of an Object in Motion''\n|[[Coteau Books]]\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quillandquire.com/google/article.cfm?article_id=12218 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130201020946/http://www.quillandquire.com/google/article.cfm?article_id=12218 |url-status=dead |archive-date=1 February 2013 |title=Eighteen Bridges\u2019 editors aspire to become Canada\u2019s New Yorker |publisher=Quill & Quire |date=23 April 2012 |accessdate=20 December 2012 }}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:lightgreen;\"\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center; font-weight:normal; background:lightgreen;\"|{{sort|1998|[[1997 in literature|1998]]}}\n|{{sortname|Joanne|Gerber|nolink=1}}\n|''In the Misleading Absence of Light''\n|[[Coteau Books]]\n|- style=\"background:lightgreen;\"\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:cen